In CV, one irreversible peak for oxidation current of DB was seen (Ea = +0.62 V; pH = 3.0, PBS) at CPE (Fig. 3A). When CPE was modified with NiMnO3 (Fig. 3B) and GQDs/NiMnO3 (Fig. 3C), a couple of reversible redox peaks appeared at Ea = +0.43 and Ec = +0.38 V, and one irreversible oxidation peak appeared at Ea = +0.85 V. The NiMnO3 caused about 2.1-fold gain in the redox current of DB compared to CPE, while the signal was significantly amplified (4.4-fold) at GQDs/NiMnO3 modified CPE, which represented fast electron-transfer kinetic. The structure of DB contains three pH-sensitive groups with pKa1 = 8.71 (catechol); pKa2 = 10.90 (amine); pKa3 = 13.68 (phenol). Both catechol moiety and phenol functional groups can undergo redox reaction above 0.0 V in PBS. Since catechol group shows a reversible behavior, the first redox peak (P1 and P2) of DB can be assigned to catechol group [30, 31], while the second irreversible signal (P3) at Ea = +0.62 V can be related to the oxidation of hydroxyl group in phenol moiety. As can be seen, the current response for catechol group was stronger than phenol moiety; therefore, the oxidation behavior of catechol group of DB was investigated in the next experiments. The maximum peak current was achieved at pH of 3.0, which was selected as optimal pH value. The anodic peak has shifted to less positive potential by increasing pH while the cathodic peak current (P2) has gradually disappeared (Fig. 4
                        ). The slope of potential vs. pH for catechol group is obtained as 63.7 mV/pH. This means that the equal number of electrons and protons are participating in oxidation mechanism of the DB. As previously proved, the oxidation pathway of catechol leads to the formation of o-benzoquinone derivative by losing two electrons and two protons:

